  "summary": "As the Carpenters' dinner concludes, Mrs. Oliver approaches Hercule Poirot and invites him to the terrace to speak privately. She slips him a note identifying Dr. Lundell as the murderer, claiming his motive was that Miss Macquart discovered he was practicing medicine illegally. Poirot expresses skepticism regarding her certainty. He informs Mrs. Oliver that someone attempted to push him onto the tracks at Gilchester station the previous night at 9:35. Mrs. Oliver notes that Dr. Lundell made a house call that night, but Poirot points out that several people's whereabouts are unverified, noting that the maid, Frieda, was at the movies and could not provide alibis for those at Hunter's Manor. Mrs. Oliver provides an alibi for Robin and his mother, stating they were playing cards with her from 8:00 to 10:30.\n\nPoirot complains about the poor conditions and food at Mrs. Samuels' residence. Muriel Samuels joins them, appearing intoxicated from gin. During the conversation, Muriel becomes emotional while discussing adoption, revealing that she was adopted and expressing her belief that mothers should never abandon their children. After the guests depart, the group visits Mrs. Upward at the Golden Chain Garden. A discussion arises regarding genetics versus environment. Mrs. Upward asserts that bloodline and genetics are the most important factors in determining character, a sentiment supported by Johnny Sams. This leads Mrs. Oliver to question the extent of hereditary traits across generations.",
